  "extracted_info": "**What the paper says about mimicry in bumblebees**\n\n| Point | Detail from the paper |\n|-------|-----------------------|\n| **Existence of mimicry** | The analyses “support mimicry in bumblebees: similar colour patterns cluster in distinct geographical zones” (section (a)). |\n| **Traditional view vs. authors’ finding** | Classic theory predicts **discrete Müllerian mimicry complexes** generated by frequency‑dependent selection. The authors find that, at a fine spatial scale, bumblebee colour patterns form a **continuum** rather than distinct clusters (Fig 1a, 1c). |\n| **Number of mimicry complexes** | They confirm the three previously recognized US complexes (Pacific Coastal, Rocky Mountain, Eastern) and identify an **additional Great Plains complex**. |\n| **Imperfect mimicry** | Imperfect mimics are common, especially in transition zones (e.g., _B. mixtus_ shows an intermediate pattern that “acts as an imperfect mimic of both regions”). |\n| **Transition zones** | Colour‑pattern transition zones are **broad, gradual** and coincide with biogeographic contact zones; they allow imperfect mimics to persist because selection pressure is weaker there. |\n| **Factors influencing mimicry precision** | • Predator discrimination ability <br>• Predator community composition and flight ranges <br>• Habitat visibility <br>• Social nature of bumblebees (kin protection reduces pressure for perfect mimicry) |\n| **Evolutionary dynamics** | The paper discusses how relaxed selection in transition zones, historical biogeography, climate, dominance drive, and genetic complexity can shape the location and width of mimicry zones. |\n| **Overall conclusion on mimicry** | “Our data suggest mimicry in bumblebees involves extensive continuous variation both in geographical and colour‑pattern space… This continuum may result from relaxed selection… allowing imperfect mimicry to persist.” |\n\n**Does the paper critique using human perception?**\n\n| Issue | Paper’s 