  "extracted_info": "**Extracted Information – Human‑perception‑based definition of North‑American bumble‑bee mimicry rings**\n\n| Section | Extracted Details (exact wording where available) |\n|---------|---------------------------------------------------|\n| **Abstract (inferred from title & opening statements)** | _“Assessing Müllerian mimicry in North American bumble bees using human perception.”_  The study “group[s] phenotypically similar bumble‑bee species into mimicry rings based on human perception of both templates and field‑based images” and then “map[s] species distributions on North American ecoregions to visually test for geographic concordance” as a way “to define North American bumble bee mimicry rings.” |\n| **Methods** | • **Generalization approach** – “we use a generalization approach to categorize North American bumble bee species into hypothesized mimicry rings.”  <br>• **Human‑perception basis** – “Mounting evidence suggest predators often generalize when viewing aposematic color patterns based on few key visual elements … several studies have shown that **human generalization is similar to the generalizations of natural predators** (24‑27).”  <br>• **Stimuli** – “we group phenotypically similar bumble bee species into mimicry rings based on **human perception of both templates and field‑based images** of these bees, employing techniques used in other analyses of mimicry (7, 8, 25, 28).”  <br>• **Data sources** – Distributional data from **iNaturalist.org** and **Discoverlife.org**; phenotypic templates from _Bumble Bees of North America_ (Williams et al. 2014).  <br>• **Analytical steps** – (i) visual‑similarity assessment of **female‑worker color‑pattern templates and photographs**, (ii) delineation of clusters (mimicry rings) from those similarity assessments, (iii) projection of each species’ range onto North American ecoregions using **ArcGIS v10** to test for geographic coherence, (iv) validation by checking whether other co‑Müllerian (sting‑capable) bees and Batesian fly mimics exhibit matching patterns and distributions. |\n| **Results** | • **Five distinct mimicry rings** identified among North‑American bumble‑bees plus a “mixed” group: <br> – **Black Mimicry Ring** (7 species; Pacific coast & NW)  <br> – **Black‑Cloaked Mimicry Ring** (5 species; tropical‑mountainous southern Mexico)  <br> – **Eastern Yellow Mimicry Ring** (8 species; Upper Midwest & Eastern NA)  <br> – **Red Mimicry Ring** (15 species; western montane & inter‑mountain ecoregions)  <br> – **Western Yellow Mimicry Ring** (8 species; western & mid‑western NA)  <br> – **Mixed Group** (19 species; no clear geographic concordance).  <br>• **Visual description** – each ring is defined by a few diagnostic colour elements (e.g., large black thorax/abdomen with yellow/white secondary bands for the Black Ring; orange/red abdominal bands for the Red Ring, etc.).  <br>• **Geographic mapping** – the rings show clear, non‑overlapping ecoregional distributions when plotted in ArcGIS (Figures 1‑2).  <br>• **Cross‑taxon validation** – non‑bumble‑bee taxa (Anthophora spp., Xylocopa virginica, Melissodes spp., robber flies _Laphria_ and _Mallophora_) exhibit colour patterns that **match the corresponding bumble‑bee rings** in the regions where they co‑occur, supporting the ring assignments. |\n| **Conclusions** | • This is “the first to treat and categorize all North American species (including those in Mexico) into **five phenotypically distinct and geographically delimited mimicry rings** and one mixed group.”  <br>• The human‑perception approach “largely agrees with those suggested by other researchers” but adds **clear geographic delimitation** and identifies a **new Mexican ring**.  <br>• The concordance of co‑Müllerian bees and Batesian fly mimics with the defined rings provides **independent ecological validation** of the rings.  <br>• The study demonstrates that **human visual generalization is a valid proxy for predator perception** in as